    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-11-16T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-11-16T00:00:00-05:00" n="23"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d23">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 711.0012/593</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Belgium</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_WB1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Whitlock</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <dateline>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">American Legation</hi>, <lb/>
                    <placeName>
                        <hi rend="italic">Brussels</hi>
                    </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-11-16">
                        <hi rend="italic">November 16, 1914</hi>.</date>
                    <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received December 7</hi>.] </dateline>
                <p rend="flushleft">No. 12]</p>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">My dear Mr. Secretary</hi>: Referring to your telegram of
                    August 17, 7 p.m.,<note n="1" xml:id="d23fn1">Not printed.</note> expressing the
                    hope that the Belgian Government would be prepared to sign a treaty similar to
                    that already negotiated with the Netherlands Government, I beg to transmit
                    herewith enclosed for your information copy of the correspondence on the subject
                    with the Belgian Government.<note n="2" xml:id="d23fn2">Not printed: substance
                        of note of October 2 from the Belgian Minister of Foreign Affairs is given
                        in the ensuing paragraph.</note>
                </p>
                <p>While previous to the war the Belgian Government had shown interest in these
                    treaties, it was, upon the outbreak of hostilities and during its subsequent
                    movement from place to place, so overtaxed and harried, that, as the Minister
                    for Foreign Affairs said, he had not the time for the calm and careful
                    consideration which he would feel obliged to give to a matter of such a
                    character.</p>
                <p>In view of the circumstances I have not insisted further and shall not again take
                    up the matter unless you desire me to do so.</p>
                <p rend="flushleft">I am [etc.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_WB1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Brand Whitlock</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
